This paper deals with medium access control protocols for wireless networks, which are typically studied in the computer science subfield of networked systems or networking and internet architecture (cs.NI). The paper also discusses the use of state information exchange between peers, which is a common topic in information theory (cs.IT). Additionally, the paper proposes a distributed protocol for forming a time-division multiple access (TDMA) schedule, which is a problem in distributed computing (cs.DC) and control systems (cs.SY). Finally, the paper mentions the adaptation of packet length and state space size, which are topics in multimedia systems (cs.MM).
